    <main>
        <h1>LeetCode 3296: Minimum Number of Seconds to Make Mountain Height Zero (C++)</h1>
        <div class="problem-description">
            <p><strong>Problem:</strong>
                You are given an integer mountainHeight denoting the height of a mountain. You are also given an integer
                array workerTimes representing the work time of workers in seconds. The workers work simultaneously to
                reduce the height of the mountain. For each unit of the mountain's height, the ith worker needs
                workerTimes[i] + workerTimes[i] * 2 + ... + workerTimes[i] * X seconds to carry out all X units. Return
                the minimum number of seconds required for all workers to reduce the mountain height to zero.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Example:</strong>
                Input: mountainHeight = 4, workerTimes = [2,1,1]<br>
                Output: 3<br>
                Explanation: Workers can reduce the mountain height optimally by distributing work based on their
                completion times. The minimum time is 3 seconds.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="code-container">
            <button class="copy-button" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button>
            <pre><code class="language-cpp">class Solution {
public:
    long long minNumberOfSeconds(int mountainHeight, vector&lt;int&gt;&amp; workerTimes) {
        priority_queue&lt;
            vector&lt;long long&gt;,
            vector&lt;vector&lt;long long&gt;&gt;,
            greater&lt;vector&lt;long long&gt;&gt;
        &gt; pq;
        for (int t : workerTimes) {
            pq.push({t, t, 1});
        }
        long long current = 0;
        while (mountainHeight--) {
            auto top = pq.top();
            pq.pop();
            long long finishTime = top[0];
            long long base = top[1];
            long long step = top[2];
            current = finishTime;
            step++;
            pq.push({finishTime + base * step, base, step});
        }
        return current;
    }
};</code></pre>
